rComments: His jokes were cute and pretty funny and he made the lectures fun and interesting. He was very helpful and always made it clear that he was available for questions or tutoring during his office hours. He was by far my favourite professor last year!

He means well and some of his jokes were all right. However this class is plagued with poor organization. It isn't a good sign when he begins *every other lecture* with "Okay, let's get started, we have a lot to cover today" before speeding through it all - that's stressful. Don't bother reading the Brophy textbook until you start exam-studying.

I just had him in the summer for Crime in England. He was a great professor, really clear, helpful. I liked that he was to the point, but also interjected a little humour into his lectures. He usually accompanied every lecture with some slides (pictures, maps, etc.) which was helpful. Great guy; loved the cute Southern accent. :-)
Very informative and clear, but a tad monotonous. There were times when I found it hard to keep my eyes open in lecture.

His lectures are a bit overwhelming but that can be due to several factors - mainly time and content (how do you explain all of WWI in 50 minutes?) However it does help that he gives the class an outline, because he tends to speak faster as a result. Laptop recommended, unless you're great at writing really quickly!

He was a great lecturer and clearly enjoyed what he was teaching. I personally found his lecture material overwhelmingly dense, which put me off at times, but maybe that's just me. I'd take another of his courses in a heartbeat.

Professor Lawrence was awesome. His first time teaching this course and he really lived up to the challenge of following Bartlett. I loved the lecture outlines and the fact that he actually talked about the tutorial readings in lecture. It made reading them more worthwhile. I liked him better than Bartlett, who's too overrated.
